<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911220-0194</DOCNO><DOCID>911220-0194.</DOCID><HL>   REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):   Meeting the ANC</HL><DATE>12/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14</SO><IN>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)</IN><NS>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND ANALYSIS (IEN)INTERNATIONAL MONETARY FUND (IMF)</NS><RE>AFRICA (AF)EASTERN EUROPE (EEU)EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)NORTH AMERICA (NME)SOUTH AFRICA (SF)SOVIET UNION (UR)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Last year, the Soviet Union's top specialist on Africabecame the first Soviet citizen to visit South Africa in 30years. While there, Irina Filatova held a meeting withmembers of the ANC and its ally, the Communist Party. To hershock, Moscow was bitterly denounced for &quot;losing&quot; its EastEuropean empire and for betraying socialism. She angrilyreplied, &quot;You wouldn't say such things if you, like me, hadbeen forced to live under socialism for any part of yourlife.&quot;   Ms. Filatova's unsettling experience should be kept inmind as 19 major political groups in South Africa sit downtoday to begin talks on a new constitution to extendpolitical rights to all individuals. The black group with themost clout, the African National Congress, hasn't shown thepolitical maturity that both its backers and skeptics hadhoped for after its legalization nearly two years ago.</LP><TEXT>   This summer, the ANC held its first party conference inmore than 20 years. Unlike other political groups, itsmeeting was secret and closed to reporters. Afterward, it wasannounced that in the future ANC members would no longerreveal whether or not they are also members of the SouthAfrican Communist Party. This month it was clear why when theSACP held its own convention. Its new general secretary isChris Hani, head of the ANC's well-armed military wing.   If South Africa's Communist Party were anything like itsbroken brethren in Eastern Europe there would be little causefor worry. But the SACP has been a virulent critic of bothMikhail Gorbachev and Boris Yeltsin, and it remains convincedthat it can create a Marxist utopia. At the party conference,delegates voted 269 to 84 to remove the word &quot;democratic&quot;from a resolution calling on the party to build a &quot;democraticSocialist&quot; society. During a recent visit to the U.S., Mr.Hani admitted the SACP would remain in alliance with the ANConly until the party itself takes power.   Whites aren't the only ones worried about the ANC and itscommunist allies. Though many black groups will sit at thenegotiating table this week, it's clear that the whitegovernment considers the ANC its major counterpart. In fact,other black groups openly complain that the ANC is trying tomonopolize black politics. The Pan Africanist Congress hasjust accused the ANC of intimidating its members, and thisweek Chief Gatsha Buthelezi of the Zulus withdrew from thetalks.   There will be several sticking points in the negotiations.The government wants to decentralize power to localauthorities to minimize the chances that one group willdominate others, as whites did under apartheid. Mr. Buthelezisays the white regime's $150 billion of industrial assetsshould be privatized. The ANC wants a highly centralizedstate and mutters about nationalizing more industry.   The U.S. can play only a limited role in South Africa, butit can help. All the players in South Africa agree thatjump-starting the stagnant economy would make the transitionto democracy easier. Some local governments and at leastthree universities have reversed policies against SouthAfrican-related investments. More should do so. Most federalgovernment sanctions have been dropped, but Washingtoncontinues to observe a 1983 law that requires it to opposeInternational Monetary Fund loans to &quot;any country thatpractices apartheid.&quot; All race-specific laws have been struckfrom the books by Pretoria, but the U.S. refuses to supportSouth African access to the IMF.   While we have differences with the IMF over policy,denying South Africa a chance to borrow at the lower interestrates that come with IMF access is indefensible. The U.S.should do what it can to revive the stalled South Africaneconomy so that all parties to the talks can discuss thecountry's future in an atmosphere that contains more hopethan despair.</TEXT></DOC>